How Do Health, Ethics and Developer Kinship Correlate to Programmer Salary?¶

1. Business Understanding¶

This notebook seeks to understand how a programmer's earnings are related to his or her attentiveness to health, ethics and kinship.

Motivating Questions¶

  1. Do health conscious programmers make more money?

  2. Will prioritizing ethical concerns in the workplace cost you?

  3. Does competitiveness or comraderie correspond to higher earnings?

The hope is that answering these questions will shine light on non-programming related activites and behaviors that may, or may not, inform earnings or earning potential.

Data Mining Goals¶

Using the responses to the Stack Overflow Data 2017 Survey (https://www.kaggle.com/stackoverflow/so-survey-2017), we will identify questions that speak to a programmer's health-consciousness, sense of ethical obligation, and feeling of kinship with fellow programmers. We will then group the respondents into cohorts based on their education degrees and years of professional coding experience in an attempt to isolate the effects of our chosen variables (health, ethics, kinship). Finally, we will create graphs to visualize the relationship between our selected variables and earnings.

Success Criteria¶

We will consider our exploration a success if we find satisfying answers to our motivating questions.

2. Data Understanding¶

We will make use of the Stack Overflow Data 2017 Survey: https://www.kaggle.com/stackoverflow/so-survey-2017. The survey polls respondents on a variety of topics, some of reach bear on our motivating quesitons.

Let's import the libraries we will need.

Numpy (http://www.numpy.org/): For data modeling

Pandas (https://pandas.pydata.org/): For data modeling and visualization

Matplotlib (https://matplotlib.org/): For data visualization

Seaborns (https://seaborn.pydata.org/): For data visualization

Survey Responses that will Help Answer our Questions¶

Income-Related Questions

  1. ConvertedSalary - Salary converted to annual USD salaries using the exchange rate on 2018-01-18, assuming 12 working months and 50 working weeks.

Variables We'd Like To Control For

  1. Employment -> Which of the following best describes your current employment status?
  2. YearsCoding -> For how many years have you coded professionally (as a part of your work)?
  3. FormalEducation -> Which of the following best describes the highest level of formal education that youve completed?

Health-Related Questions

  1. Exercise -> In a typical week, how many times do you exercise?
  2. SkipMeals -> In a typical week, how many times do you skip a meal in order to be more productive?
  3. ErgonomicDevices -> What ergonomic furniture or devices do you use on a regular basis? Please select all that apply.

Ethics-Related Questions

  1. EthicsChoice -> Do you report or otherwise call out the unethical code in question?
  2. EthicsReport -> Do you report or otherwise call out the unethical code in question?
  3. EthicalImplications -> Do you believe that you have an obligation to consider the ethical implications of the code that you write?

Kinship-Related Questions

  1. AgreeDisagree1 -> To what extent do you agree or disagree with each of the following statements? I feel a sense of kinship or connection to other developers
  2. AgreeDisagree2 -> To what extent do you agree or disagree with each of the following statements? I think of myself as competing with my peers

3. Data Preparation: Cleaning and Deriving New Features¶

Drop Rows Missing Salary¶

Since our motivating questions rely on knowing the respondent's salary, we have to drop rows that don't have this information

Drop rows missing salary and with salary of 0 - presumably students and job hunters

In [431]:
results_df = results_df.dropna(subset=['ConvertedSalary'])
results_df = results_df[results_df.ConvertedSalary != 0]

# How many respondents remain

print("Number of remaining respondents: ", results_df.shape[0])

Number of remaining respondents:  46860

Implement Controls¶

To make sure we're controlling for as many variables unrelated to health, ethics and kinship as possible, we need to group our respondents into cohorts that remove as many other factors as possible.

Based on the response questions, it seems reasonable to group based on employment status, years employed (since the longer you've worked the more you are likely to make), and education degree (since this could impact earnings).

Control for Employment Status¶

Only keep respondents employed full-time for fair comparison. Otherwise, we will be comparing the salaries of students, retirees, part-time workers, freelancers, etc. to those working consistently, which could skew our findings.

In [432]:
results_df = results_df[results_df.Employment == 'Employed full-time']
print('Number of remaining respondents: ', results_df.shape[0])

Number of remaining respondents:  39266

We have to do this since we are going to be grouping our respondents based on the number of years they have spent coding. Creating a dummy "no_response" variable will not be a reliable grouping method since it could contain programmers with highly varying years of experience.

4. Visualization and Evaluation¶

Now that our data is clean and we have all the features we need, it's time to visualize the relationship between health, ethics and kinship and earning.

First, let's set our matplotlib defaults

In [472]:
plt.rcParams['figure.titlesize'] = 24
plt.rcParams['axes.labelsize'] = 16
plt.rcParams['xtick.labelsize'] = 14

plt.rcParams['figure.autolayout'] = True

Since we will be creating a number of visuals, let's define a re-usable function that will make the same chart for our different variables.

In [473]:
def salary_factor_charts(x_var, x_label, mean_or_median, df, add_regression = False) :
    
    """ 
    Creates factor chart that plots a variable against salary
  
    The factor charts will use EducationDegree control as the columnns and the CodingProfesionally control as the rows. 
  
    Parameters: 
    x_var (string): Name of the variable to plot against salary while control for Education and Years Coding professionally
    
    x_label (string): Label for the X axis
    
    mean_or_median (string) : String that must be 'mean' or 'median' that determines the estimator function to use
    
    df (string): Name of the dataframe containing the data to chart
    
    add_regression (boolean) : Determine whether or not to overlay a regression line.
    Returns: Nothing 
  
    """
    
    if (mean_or_median == 'Mean') :
        estimator_func = np.mean
    elif (mean_or_median == 'Median') :
        estimator_func = np.median
    else :
        print ('Please enter either "Mean" or "Median" for the third argument')
        return None
    
    g = sns.factorplot(x=x_var, y='ConvertedSalary', col='EducationDegree', row='CodingProfessionally', data=df, sharex=False, sharey=False, aspect=1.75, kind='bar', legend=False, estimator=estimator_func)
    
    if (add_regression) :
        g = g.map(sns.regplot, x_var, 'ConvertedSalary', scatter=False, fit_reg=True)
        
    for ax in g.axes.flat :
        ax.set_ylabel(mean_or_median +' Salary (USD)')
        ax.set_xlabel(x_label)
    
    return None

Conclusions and Final Thoughts¶

Its worth pointing out that correlation is not causation! For example, the above graphs do not indicate that leading a healthy lifestyle causes higher earnings. Its possible that those with higher earnings have more resources to lead health lifestyles. Similarly, maybe the richer among us have the luxury of considering the ethical implications of their code while those who are earn less dont.

What we can conclude, however, is that attending to ones health and ethics does not seem to cost you, and may even benefit a programmers bottom line.

When it comes to kinship, it seems that as we gain in professional experience, earnings accrue more to the competitors than to the collaborators.
